</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tesar" authorityYear="1945" box="[981,1107,1933,1959]" class="Insecta" family="Aphodiidae" genus="Carinaulus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[981,1107,1933,1959]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="229">Carinaulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the new species can, at first glance, be easily distinguished by frontoclypeal suture with four gibbosities (
<figureCitation box="[1014,1098,1969,1996]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–20" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1726,1750]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,184,1692]" captionTargetId="figure-15@7.[151,1436,181,1702]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 13–20. Heads and pronotum. 13, Trichiorhyssemus immaturus Minkina, new species, holotype, female, head; 14, T. immaturus Minkina, new species, holotype, female, pronotum; 15, Agrilinus matusiaki Minkina, new species, holotype, male, head; 16, Agrilinus inexspectatus (Balthasar, 1935), male, head; 17, Agrilinus striatus (Schmidt, 1910), male, head; 18, Carinaulus meghalayensis (Červenka, 2000), male, head; 19, Gilletianus miurai Minkina, new species, holotype, male, head; 20, Gilletianus sundainsulanus Ochi, Kon &amp; Kawahara, 2014, male, head." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6810124" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6810124/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="229">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
